LineComment.Text:
What's with the fbWinCCTime & Time_Of_Day variables?
When WinCC displays a TIME variable, it shows it as an integer number of milliseconds. So 5 minutes is 300,000ms. Not very intutive. For longer times, like 1h20min, it's 4,800,000ms. To get a nice display of HH:MM:SS on the screen, and be able to enter time in this format also, the Time_Of_Day variable type has to be used.
All regulators & other structs use TIME because it's the right type to use, and the same is used everywhere for uniformity. WinCC requires Time_Of_Day for usability. So instead of wrecking the structure and regularity of all those beautiful structs, a conversion is done here (from TIME to TOD and back) to make TIME values "just work" in WinCC. It's ugly but it works, and frees the structs to be made the way the design requires, not the way WinCC requires.
